caption: The food was satisfactory and the place was nice and clean. We were enjoying our night, Feb. 12, 2021 Lunar New Year and we just arrived from New York. We were aware of our reservation. We were almost done, and our bottle of wine almost down, but we were in the mood  We asked our server if we can still order, telling him we have limited time left. He said it should be ok,.so we ordered one more. Then someone came to apologize for the delay. Maybe he is the manager or perhaps owner. Twice we were told about the delay. Finally it came. And when we just started to eat, the lady by the door told us our reservation is over. I tried to explain the situation, but she said she cant do anything. We didnt want to make a scene, so we stood up and asked that our food be taken out. Surely, the other new customer could have been accommodated on another table while we finish our meal. So disappointed. Also, it is a Chinese resto and it is Chinese new year. Surely the staff can be taught of a greeting on this important and auspicious day. It is just 4 syllables. I greeted the server and he was clueless and just laughed at what i said.

This restaurant has Door Dash listed on their website as one of the official services that can be used to order dinner from them. I placed an order in advance, only to have it be cancelled by Door Dash at the time it should have been arriving. The restaurant offered the excuse that they are having issues with Door Dash, but could not explain why they continue to have the service listed on their website as one of their officially endorsed delivery services. If the service is causing them to leave their customers high and dry, you would think they would at least remove the link from their website until they are able to resolve their disputes with the company. The meal was for a celebration of the lunar new year; for my family, this is like being stuck with no dinner on Thanksgiving. The manager I spoke with refused to admit any culpability and somehow thought gift certificates would make up for the ruined holiday, for which he offered zero empathy or apology, just continued to blame Door Dash and thought my frustration with the situation was somehow unreasonable.  Is the food any good? I have no idea.
Delicious Hong Kong food in trendy blanden alley. Contactless ordering from your table and great service. Loves the sesame noodles and brisket buns!

This restaurant has the unique combination of wonderful and interesting decor combined with excellent food. The Basil Pork Bao was particularly good. The only "complaint" was the green bean dish was way too much for two people and we had plenty of leftovers! I loved the overall vibe and interiors decorating of the space too.
Fantastic takeaway meal all around. Flavors were spot on.
Best fried rice in town.

Fantastic!! Having lived and traveled in Asia quite a bit, I was prepared to be disappointed. Instead, I was super impressed. The atmosphere is amazing, and the food is even better. I recommend the Mantou Buns and the Beef Cheung Fun. 100% recommend.

Had an amazing time on a late night Thursday. Arrived here after at bad experience at Columbia room, and sat at the bar with lesandro bartending. Tried four cocktails and four items off the late night menu. Everything was incredible, and very unique. Our bartender was exceptionally descriptive and helpful with guiding us through what we were experiencing.  One of the best and unique culinary experiences I've ever had. I cannot recommend tiger fork highly enough.  EDIT: A year and a half later, this place still stays true as one of my favorite restaurants of all time. I think of it often, when I eat similar style, albeit worse, food. Please, if you read this review, give this place a chance. You will remember the uniqueness for years to come.
Definitely recommend this Blagden Alley gem. Authentic food and fantastic atmosphere. Cocktails were intriguing and the staff was friendly/knowledgeable. I will definitely be back!

The food here is incredibly tasty. The ambiance is great too. We sat outside- it was charming. I would strongly recommend trying any of the drinks in the menu. They make it a point to develop interesting cocktails.

Amazing spot in a quiet alley with outdoor seating and heaters. I loved all the dishes I tried here—you especially need to get the pork belly! The service was friendly and quick, and I appreciate the safety measures they’ve taken during the pandemic.
overrated and overpriced. food comes out seconds after you order which makes me think dishes are prepared in advance and then heated up. far better Chinese street food in rockville at half the price

No bathroom.  I drove a long distance to come here and pick up an order.  On arrival I was told that due to COVID liability reasons, bathrooms are not available.  The location was a bit difficult to find, a ways down a back alley, and parking was very challenging.  Wouldn't recommend coming here at night.
Amazing, one of my favorite restaurants and I only went once so far
Great takes on Chinese street eats.
(Translated by Google) Scepter  (Original) الصولجان
Delicious and service from some true professionals. Very pleasant outside.

tl;dr Staff does not care about their guests once they pay for the food. Also, staff doesn't know how to work with clients. The food was plain and overpriced. I do not understand how this restaurant is so overhyped.  At the restaurant, you order your food through their App and pay instantly, it was convent, but staff did not seem to care about our table once we paid for the meal.  We had a table at the outdoor patio, and we could not fully enjoy the atmosphere because the restaurant's window was boarded up like it was a war-zone. When the weather got a little bit unstable, a waiter came with boxes and said that we must leave now because of the rain. It was understandable, but you expect to hear something more when you just finished the appetizer and were waiting for the main dishes.  The first main dish came in a box, but we had to wait for the other one and moved inside of the restaurant. We waited for 10 minutes, and nobody brought us anything. Then I asked one of the staff members who were chatting with each other about the status of my order, and it turned out that it was not cooked yet.... 15 minutes later, we got the other dish.  Once we got home with a bitter experience at the restaurant, we hoped to enjoy the food. Well, it was tasteless...
Great place, nice ambience, the servers were very warm and receptive, the meal (prawn fried rice) was a culinary bliss of oryza sativa, best I’ve had in a long while. Will definitely be coming again
Great food authentic. Four d this gem after COVID so only have had the condensed menu cannot wait to try the full one
Really cool ambiance. Very lively place. Good for a fun date. Overpriced. Food was just okay.
Their healthy cocktail menus make me get more drinks. Love their fish, noodles and fried rice. Wish they had more desserts menu.
Wonderful foods, delicious cocktails, trendy style and fun servers.
Cocktails are fantastic. Fried rice, pork belly, spicy buns all great. Team is super attentive.

The online reservation system was showing availability for 7:00 but would not let us book, so we walked into the restaurant and were denied seating although there were lots of open tables, just because their online system wasn’t working properly. When we asked if we could call next time, the (unhelpful) hostess said no and seemed to not care or take any measures to fit us in.
The fried rice here is nothing short of amazing. My favorite restaurant in this neighborhood.

This place not only has great food but also great drinks. Quick recommendations would be the Humble Plate of Wontons and the Victoria Park cocktail! Tiger Fork is a true gem in Blagden alley and worth the trip!
Rushed! Rushed! Five courses in 20 minutes! And - a small table that slanted so we could only use half of it. We were holding dishes in our hands. Never again!
Bar is extensive, menu seemed limited with a few good options.  Trendy joint tucked away in an alley way near the DC convention center.

My friend wanted to come here for her birthday so of course I had to make the birthday girl hella happy! I like how this place is in the cut-nice and tucked away. The ambience is romantic, extremely dim lighting. The food was fresh and I dont have any complaints other than like the cucumber dish we got was extremely salty, so wouldn't order that again. But its a very cute place
Went with a large group and tried a bunch of different food, everything was delicious. Service was quick, drinks were well made and quick. Well worth the trip
Great environment and decoration but the food is just okay
Delicious, very well balanced food, flawless service and very nice atmosphere. Definitely on my list to return
Try their Pork Shank. Delicious! The place is cozy and the staff is friendly

The food was really tasty but the service was disappointing. The forbidden salad was really unique and I hadnt tasted anything like it before. The brisket noodles were awesome and the tofu was solid too. The disappointing part was the service where we had to try and flag them down for water refills or to put in our order. Also, was a bit disappointed that after making reservations weeks in advance that they sat us at the “chefs table” bar next to the kitchen. We could hear the orders being yelled in and out, and some tiffs in the kitchen. The food was a high 4, and the service was a generous 3. Would consider going back but would try and opt for the table.

Smashed Cucumber Salad (4/5 NOMs) Sometimes eating veggies is not just good for you, but also tastes amazing, like this starter – Smashed Cucumber Salad. I won’t deny, we were a bit surprised about the size of it. Though maybe it’s normal, as this comes from the Dai Pai Dong menu section which refers to a type of open-air food stalls in Hong Kong. There are no crazy toppings or seasoning here, it’s a simple dish containing cucumbers, garlic, chili, and sesame. The combination of drinks and this salad are a great way to start a very nomnom dinner. While small, it’s great for sharing; two guests can easily share one but order a few for a larger group. I guess it’s called smashed because instead of cutting them, they smashed the cucumbers? I wonder with what and how. Maybe we should try smashing at home?  Beef Chow Fun (5/5 NOMs) Time to move onto the main course with a good Beef Chow Fun from the rice and noodles section. We are a big fan of wide rice noodles and were super excited to dig into this one. Plus, we were very hungry at this point. Beef Chow Fun is a staple of Cantonese cuisine originally from Hong Kong, and it’s so common that at this point everyone has tried their own take on it. If a restaurant can’t make this right, then you may as well leave. You can tell by our good rating that they did not disappoint at Tiger Fork. We are big fans of the thick rice noodles, bok choy, and juicy brisket that pulled this dish together. If you’re a fan of Beef Chow Fun and noodles, then this is a perfect dish for you. We enjoyed this dish so much that we left the plate sparkly clean.  Fried Rice Chicken & Chinese Sausage (4/5 NOMs) When going to a Chinese restaurant, it’s almost obligatory for you to order fried rice, and at Tiger Fork, we are starting with Fried Rice Chicken & Chinese Sausage. We are big fans of Chinese sausage, which you can buy at any H Mart or other Asian markets. Portion-wise it’s perfect, and enough to share with a large group.  Fried Rice Fish & Prawn (5 NOMs) This isn’t just any rice, it’s Fried Rice with Fish and Prawn. We actually like this one more than the Chicken & Chinese Sausage version. Portion and price-wise, both fried rice dishes are identical. You won’t go wrong with either one, but we felt that this one was better.  Humble Plate of Chili Wontons (3/5 NOMs) It’s always good to be humble, but that’s not us, so we eat humble like a plate of Humble Plate of Chili Wontons. The presentation is fun with these little bites floating in the spicy sauce. These wontons are stuffed with shrimp, chicken, and ginger. Even the spicy sauce didn’t hit that much-needed spot.  Pork Ribs (5 NOMs) A beautiful presentation and amazing taste make for our favorite dish of the night – the Pork Ribs. Not much to say here besides the fact that these ribs are amazing! Covered in soy, ginger, and Happy Lady spice which is also known as Lao Gan Ma Chili Crisp Sauce. These ribs were cooked to perfection with meat that falls off the bone. With so much sauce, it makes for one very messy dish. Good thing they give you some wipes! However, we all know that you will lick your fingers clean. It’s so good, maybe even a neighbor’s finger.  BBQ Platter (5/5 NOMs) It’s the one plate of meat to rule them all – the BBQ Platter with three different kinds of meaty goodness in one! What’s not to love with its crispy pork belly, char siu (Cantonese roasted pork), and soy chicken? Plus, served with some side sauces, veggies, and rice. Every piece of meat was so good that we just naturally enjoyed it slowly to savor every bite. Our favorite (no surprise), was the crispy pork belly. The rice was also surprisingly good, very sticky, and soft.

My brunch friend called in awol after eating something bad last night. They were still incredibly kind and still gave me a great table. Great servoce. I had the chow fun. Delicious. The table next to me couldn't get enough of the congee.Definitely coming again.

This was fabulous. Make sure to order the buns from the “secret” menu - they are amazing. The chow fun was also outstanding. I think the picture of the bubble waffle says it all - yes that is pocky and cocoa pebbles! The service and atmosphere was on point. It is a bit hidden in Blagden Alley, which adds to the vibe. Great value for the price and I can’t wait to go back.

Tiger Fork absolutely lives up to its reputation as one of the best Asian restaurants in DC.  It knocks its take on Hong Kong street food out fo the park,, which is extremely evident by its pan fried dumplings and pork ribs.  Their fried rice and rice noodle dishes are amazing too, specifically the Beef Chow Fun dish with brisket.  I also highly recommend sitting at the bar overlooking the kitchen so you can see all of the intricate details that go into making all of the dishes.  I can't wait to get back here again soon.
The herbal medicine inspired cocktails are very tasty.
Awesome food

I realize I’m in the minority when i write this but i went to tiger fork last night expecting an amazing meal and was so disappointed. Let me preface this by saying I’ve lived in nyc and Chinatown was my FAVORITE area for food. I definitely consider myself to be somewhat of a noodle enthusiast. So since I’ve moved to DC I’ve been on the hunt for a place to get some good noodles. I first saw tiger fork on Instagram and immediately wanted their beef noodle soup that was advertised, it looks delicious as well as the chili wontons. I went last night and the waiter first had no idea Tiger Fork had beef noodle soup, it wasn’t on the menu and he said he’s been working there for several months and never heard of it (they posted the soup two weeks ago). We ended up ordering the beef chow fun and chili wontons. The beef was bland and lacking flavor, the noodles were also flavorless. I asked for some chili oil to spice it up and the CHILI OIL HAD LITTLE TO NO FLAVOR which I’ve never experienced. All in all I’d say it was an okay meal. Not great, not terrible just bland.

The traditional Chinese medicine cocktails are very inventive and flavorful, and the steamed fish was solid! Cool ambiance too, worth a visit. Be warned it's quite expensive, as expected for downtown DC!
Excellent and authentic food and culture

This was my first visit to Tiger Fork.  The space is great, the employees are friendly and very knowledgeable, and the cocktails are truly inventive, but the food was just good.  We had mushroom spring rolls, chilli wontons, char siu (chinese pork) and snow pea leaves.  Nothing had that taste of... I can't wait to have this again! Went to TF with the same friend I went to Chiko with for the first time.  In comparison, almost every dish at Chiko had an amazing taste that we couldn't wait to try again.  And although it's a long haul, Mama Chang's in Fairfax has spectacular chinese food. I will try Tiger Fork again, but it's not a rush.
They offer really cool drinks, and best fried rice I have ever had!!! If you love spice as me, you should definitely ask for their chili source!!! Wonton was okay - a bit salty and pricey!!

It’s always been difficult for us to get a reservation here because it is so popular! I now understand why! We sat at the chef’s counter which was a very cool experience. All of the food was out of this world. The staff is very knowledgeable about every dish. You have to order the bubble waffle for dessert!
Beef Chow Fun is so good here. The location is amazing. Love coming here!
Try their Pork Shank. Delicious! The place is cozy and the staff is friendly.
Excellent meal. And the bartender makes delicious vermouth, which he offered as a free sample while I was waiting. Strongly recommend you brave the dark silent alley to find this place!
Great Chinese in a hidden location
One of the best places I have ever had dinner. If you love asian food you'll love Tiger Fork, every dish here is full of flavor, you can't go wrong with any disk!
Delightful Asian cuisine extremely close to convention center! Down the side alley and you're there!
Lovely atmosphere. Interesting and tasty food. Ask for their secret menu.

This place is delicious. A visit to Blagdon Alley is always a good time with the unique atmosphere outside the restaurants. I highly recommend asking about the daily specials or "secret menu". We had the fried beef buns off it which were delicious.  We also had the smashed cucumber salad which was very tasty. We drank some sake and tried baijiu which I highly recommend trying as they are very knowledgeable about it there.  We shared the beef chow fun as the main entree which was plenty for two people. Lastly we finished with the egg tart which was a perfectly sized dessert. Will definitely be back!

The hostess mentioned the wait was one hour and we waited for only 15 min. The food was decent but service was really not up to the price tag. The waitress took the water bottle to refill and never return.
Delicious but always busy. Make reservations or play musical chairs to sit at the bar. Love this place. Excellent food and drinks. Fun location!

Food was good.  In the middle of a nondiscript warehouse area.  There's a "family" table in the center so make a reservation if that's not your style. Food was prepared well, but was not the most flavorful.  Our server was helpful and very friendly. Bathroom was very clean.
This is definitely one of the coolest restaurants in DC. Either late night at the bar or with a date at dinner. Glenn is always very accommodating.
Very small area. Make reservations or your party will likely end up looking for another spot to eat.
Elite Chinese food.. Beyond expectations..
The fried rice was amazing. The stew had great layers of flavor. Nice finish with the bubble waffle!

It was great when I went the first time but disappointing the second time. I wonder if it’s because of the diminishing marginal return, but I won’t go again.... ps I ordered their bubble waffle twice and apparently the first time was way better.

As two people we had a seat where we could observe the drama of the kitchen. I vaguely remember reserving seats here via resy. My spouse is a spice wimp but we enjoyed frog legs and the beef brisket noodles with no problem. Of course we informed our server about our concerns beforehand. We had a lovely dinner.
Okay Chinese fusion place. Had bbq mix plate, beef chow fun, and wontons. Wontons and mixed drinks were the highlights of our night.
Food is really good.  Loved the cucumber salad and fish ball appetizers.  Only a little spicy. Great for someone who can't handle heat, like me.
Service was good and food was just okay nothing special or stand out.
Delicious but salty

The flavor of the food is good, but too sweet for my liking. Seems to be catered for americans, so if you are looking for something authentic, don't think this is for you. Nevertheless, the ambiance is good.
Great place to share plates with friends. Delicious food that is an upscale take on Chinese street food.
"Deep flavor with breadth, very good" -my bf
Bib gourmand worthy for sure.  The fried rice was fantastic and the cumber salad incredible.  Service was wonderful as well.  Highly recommend.
Very interesting and tasty menu.
Great food. Amazing cocktails

I was looking for the kind of dim sum that comes on carts and accidentally found this place instead, but it was really good. It's not "traditional", it's "upscale", but at least the atmosphere and the flavor are truly indicative of that fact.
Great food, cocktails, and service
Wonderful, flavorful food. Everything I had was delicious and it made me want to come back to try more.
Very informal but excellent. Ate at the bar super friendly service.

Scrumptious food and great service. I tried to get a reservation at Tiger Fork a few times before I actually got to try it. It was always booked. But It was well worth the persistence. I enjoyed everything about it. The decor, the vibes, and of course the delicious food.  I particularly loved the Cheung Fun, Fried Rice on Special, The Chairman’s Clams, and the Fish Balls.  I can’t wait to go back to sample all the other dishes. The service was perfect. Sidney was attentive and made great recommendations.  Glenn, the manager, was a wonderful host. Keep up the good work, guys, and thank you for an excellent experience.

Beautiful decor, inspired Asian cuisine, medicinal alcoholic beverages? This place is destined to become a landmark location. Please try the Japanese Whiskey bar, the Frog Legs, The Kowloon Buns..... Shoot!! Try everything!!!
Great place staff is great food is delicious one dish after the other Delicious
This place is amazing. The pork belly was out of this world!!

The only thing worse than the food was the service. Bland, uncreative, and just not enjoyable. The service was even worse. It took over twenty minutes to get anyone's attention to even get a check, forget anything else resembling a focus on service.
it is upscale dining. Surely, it is quite expensive than normal Chinese restaurant. I do believe this is a fine dining style of Chinese. I highly recommend to visit here.

Not bad food... but poor customer service! They charged more than we ate at first(70dollars). So I asked to recheck. And they showed me another bill with something we didn't order, saying though the list was different but they put the money we should pay and then they discount 10 dollars(total 50 dollars). But for me it seemed unclear(On Earth which restaurant show that kind of bill?????). So I asked menu and calculated by my self and it turned out the total was about $40. I felt insulted.
Very cool place. Traditional Chinese medicine version of cocktails is a very unique concept that is awesome to drink and think about.
Great spot!!
Eclectic Chinese ( Hong Kong) Unlike Typical Chinese (Cantonese)  Great Ambiance Superb
Excellent.  Ordered 6 dishes for sharing and all were really, really good.
Place look good but food not really Asian nor Chinese. Our meal was way too sweet which for a fried rice is weird. Maybe good for a drink?

(Translated by Google) American Chinese food, sweet and terrible. A Guangzhou fried rice is actually sweet, and it can actually eat sugar. unbearable.  (Original) 美式中餐，甜得要命。一個廣州炒飯居然是甜的，裡頭居然能吃出糖粒。無法忍受。

Tiger Fork in Blagden Alley has a great ambiance and delicious food. I've been twice (once for dinner and once for brunch) and both times were awesome. The cocktails are interesting and worth trying (plus they are pretty delicious), and the teas they have for brunch are beautiful. All of the food sounds interesting and we haven't had a bad dish so far (though I do recommend staying away from the smashed cucumber salad unless you really, really like pickles). The service is good as well! Even if you don't have a reservation,  I recommend walking in and seeing if there's seating at the large communal table. You will not be disappointed with this taste of Hong Kong in DC.
Very tasty fish fried rice and yummy noodles

The server/bartender who waited on me was fantastic and several times went above & beyond to care for me.  The food was knock it out of the park on point & drinks were mysteriously tantalizing.  I ate at 7p & my food took less than 10 minutes to arrive.
(Translated by Google) It was very good and I agree  (Original) Estuvo muy bien y estoy de acuerdo
Great food
I loved the food and the atmosphere. The staff is great as well.

Ordered only from the appetizer side of the menu and was not disappointed. The stand out for us was the Chili Tofu with preserved crab, had to order a second one. (UPDATE: They took this wonderful dish off the menu, so sad) The cocktails were inventive and very well crafted. I enjoyed the 8 o'clock light show as it is rum forward. Looking forward to a return trip to try the mains. Would add a extra 1/2 star if I could.
Great food. Great service. Reasonable price. 100% would reccomend to anyone looking for a good sit down Chinese restaurant in DC.
It was great. Awesome service and wonderful atmosphere. Tasty food that was served  perfectly. Highly recommend the menu.

Had a wonderful visit as always. This time we came in with no reservations (8/1 around 8:45) and both staff at the door were so sweet in trying to accommodate my pregnant wife and I asap, found us a seat at the communal table. Both of us work as managers in restaurants and wanted to take the time to mention that those two exemplify what we are looking to develop on our staffs! Meal was great too!
Bland flavors on the pork ribs, only slightly better for the wontons.  Very pricey for quantity and apparently none spent on flavors.
We sat at the bar and had an absolute blast with the bartenders. They made it a really fun experience and the food was very good.. Drinks even better
Took my partner and crime here for his birthday dinner and he loved it. Flavors were good, service was okay, and the food quality was perfect.

Came here for brunch with my mom and it really fell short. I’m not sure if this was an isolated incident, but the service was painfully slow. I don’t fault the wait staff because I don’t think they control when food comes out of the kitchen but it was a bit disappointing. It was 45 minutes between when my food and my mom’s came out. Luckily, we were able to share mine. But that would have been awkward in any other circumstances. And after a wait that long, the food just wasn’t as great as I anticipated. I wanted to like it so bad but sadly, I’ll be skipping it.

as Chinese myself, this is the most disgusting chinese food I have ever experienced. 5 of us order 7 dishes, all of them are not freshly made. Salty, so much sugar and unpleasent serice. expensive as well. no idea how they get Michelin 2019.
Just went for drinks, bartender was very attentive without being pushy. Very cool decor and atmosphere
Great food, and creative drinks.
Food and service are excellent. Cocktails are out of this world. Best friend rice I've ever had, and that's saying something. Fried dishes can be heavy, but it works. Service is phenomenal.

Food is delicious here, but I wouldn't order the Bubble Waffle again.  The atmosphere has a very low dimmed setting, and the service was good. Ordered the BBQ Plate Combo, and it was pretty much a sampler to try various types of food. My favorite is the crispy pork belly, where it was really crispy, and the meat was tender. The char siu is pretty tasty. The soya chicken was average, but nothing amazing. Overall, the food quality was good.  My only complaint is the bubble waffle where the waffle is below room temperature, which should be hot considering it should just come off the waffle maker; however, they just have these pre-made sitting on the waffle maker so they aren't made to order where you can enjoy it more like you would at other cafes that sells bubble waffles.

The food is amazing! I would give Tiger Fork more than 5 stars if I could! Both the atmosphere and food are exceptional. It's just off the beaten path, hidden down an alley way, giving it a very hidden gem feel. Once inside the little touches make all the difference.  For dinner we started with the fish balls appetizer--it was melt in your mouth amazing! Then we had the whole fish, which was fried in a sweet and sour sauce, the chicken fried rice, and the beef chow fun noodles. To top it off with the Milk Tea was amazing, a tired and true classic down to perfection. Each dish had its own original spin. You'll just have to try it yourself to see what's in store. You won't be disappointed!
Gets so damn loud if it's packed, cannot have a normal conversation, almost ear ringing levels...they should invest in some sound deadening. Food was pretty nice though!

Had the cold dan dan noodles. Excellent dish composition and quality. Spice was significant, but just the right pairing for someone with a bit of tolerance.  Later on a weeknight, the place was absolutely packed and loud. I was lucky to get a single seat at the bar quickly.

I loved this restaurant. The food was flavorful with generous portions, and the ambiance of the restaurant was really cool. I definitely recommend trying the Beef Chow Fun. I highly recommend coming here, be it for a date or hanging with friends.

What a super cool place! If you can find Tiger Fork (which is part of the charm) you will be rewarded with wonderfully delicious food and service. Mostly family style dishes that please the taste buds. Bring your appetite!

Phenomenal food in a little hole in the wall down an alley with amazing ambience from the moment you step inside. The service was outstanding! Definitely hope to visit Tiger Fork again on our next trip to D.C.
Everything is very good and the staff is awesome. Glad to see both bubble waffles and eggs tarts on the menu!
Located in a rather unusual place, but was packed with a great crowd with good vibes.
This place has awesome noodles and just overall great food.

Really cool ambiance with incredibly friendly staff. The drinks are eccentric and add to the vibrancy of the atmosphere. I can see why it was so hard to get a table here, but I would highly recommend the bar for seating as it really seems to be the "center" of the restaurants design. the chef's table also seemed neat, and if I stumble back here I will definitely aim there. Food wasn't too far off the beaten path for Chinese street eats, but definitely very tasty. Cucumbers could have been a little spicier, but my entree was fantastic so I'll let it slide.

Great place! Everything we ordered was a amazing and there was great service. We ordered the fried eggplant, the beef noodles and the pork shoulder.  The beef noodles are a must. They have an extensive drink menu. It’s a great date place! The decorations are cool and eclectic.

Definitely going back! If you don’t have a reservation, go early and you might be able to snag a seat at the bar. Fantastic food, well worth the wait and price.  Get the pork ribs, two if you’re hungry.

Excellent food, generous portions, courteous staff, and a nifty location. Dishes are served family style. For a party of two, we had an appetizer of dumplings, a gargantuan serving of delicious green beans, and the fish of the day. I cannot understate how impressive the green beans and fish were.  All for a reasonable price, no less.

This place is nothing short of amazing. The fried rice and beef chow fun are two of my favorites. The late night menu is solid as well. Perfect combination of drinks, food and nice people. The staff is ultimately star makes this a 5 star experience. Everyone is friendly, attentive and just so cool. My favorite Blagden Alley location.
Better than you'd imagine (or fear) for heavily internationalized hipster-style approximations of imagined Chinese food. Very pricey but tasty.

Not impressed. Brunch was over-priced and average. Service was terrible (except for Chris and the hostess). There was only one waitress working, and she was also the bartender? Food was over-sauced and too salty and sweet.  We ordered 8 different things, nothing was that good. I'm ok with paying a premium for delicious foods, but this was not worth it. Regular dim sum at any other place tastes better and cost 1/3 what we paid.  Disappointed. Don't understand the positive reviews.  Update- there was a shell in my shumai.
Love this place.

Review for brunch: if you’re looking for dim sum, go elsewhere. Food was oversauced and overpriced. The rice noodle rolls came drowning in a sweet and sour sauce. The cucumbers, overwhelmed with sugar and vinegar, were missing the signature crunch that makes this dish refreshing. The congee was without the umami depth usually cooked into the broth. The saving grace was the decor (a cool vibe) and the perfectly soft-boiled egg in the congee, but even then the egg was weirdly sweet? Given that we overheard another exiting group exclaim “Michelin-guide recommended?? This place?!” we clearly weren’t alone in our disappointment.
....they twisted the congee into an unpleasant dish...not good as a food choice regardless if it is close to Chinese.   Could be fine as a bar if you are looking for drinks though...

Phenomenal!!! The best service I’ve ever had. The staff was friendly, quick, and polite. The food was fresh and tasty. The drinks are mixed with traditional chinese medicine- I wish I was in the city longer so I could come back!
(Translated by Google) A nice restaurant with a delicious menu.  (Original) Un restaurante bonito con un delicioso menú.

Unclassy and Rushed Service. I visited Tiger Fork in May 2019 and experienced some of the worst service I've ever had at any DC restaurant. After being seated, the server did not come back to our table for about 15 minutes. We immediately placed our food and drink orders. The food came out first and within 7 minutes, the waitress asked us if we were ready for the check. I had not even gotten my drink yet! The server apologized about the drink and brought it to me a few minutes later but then asked again if we were almost done with dinner and whether we wanted a box for our leftovers. We had the food for only 10 minutes and she was already trying to kick us out!  Lastly, on our way out, we heard another server telling a separate table about the "daily specials," which our server never told us about. The food was alright, nothing to rave about, but the service made the experience awful.
Food was really good. Ambiance is amazing. Disappointed because I didn’t find a tiger in my fork.
Good bar
Worst cocktails we've ever had
Tried seven dishes and not one was good. Slow service despite being empty.

SO amazing. Fantastic and creative cocktails, even better food. Only qualm is that they didn't pack all of the food from the BBQ plate in our to to box. They left out the 2 sauces, the kimchi, and the rice... bummer.
Incredible food and cocktails.

So I can as served by Ben the bartender and his cocktails rock-Do not be afraid to skip the set menu and just tell him what you like(tastes, flavors and type of alcohol ) and he can make-The clams dish is the best I have had since 1967 in Delaware where you get almost 50 clams but in this case you get this killer Asian broth and rice on the side that his heads and shoulders above the old school version  Google needs to get the address right cause your app does not get you here

A nice bar and restaurant hidden away in an alley in Shaw district. There are a couple of vegetarian dishes available to try. The cucumber salad and sweet & sour eggplant was really nice. Cocktails are certainly unique and nice. Place had good ambience and was quite busy late night Saturday.
Not worth the price

Exterior of this building is very cool. Instagram Worthy if well taken.  Food was very good, little salty, but order a bowl of rice (which they give u lot) and it's fine. Food plating and decoration is good too. Fancy yet cozy place to hang out. Price is very reasonable as well.

This is the spot man I freaking love this place, the have their own unique way of preparing drinks and food Asian style and its amazing. If you are craving Asian and fun this place is the spot you need to go.

I might be expecting too much because I'm Cantonese... I'm sorry but this is not Cantonese or modernized Cantonese food. This is definitively Americanized Cantonese food being called differently. But seriously, I don't even care if it's Cantonese or not, I just want tasty food! The only reason I'm giving them an extra star is because of the BBQ quail. Other than the food, it looks cool but I don't think it's cool enough to pay $50 per person for a meal like this.

Tiger Fork As we walked down 9th st into a alley which was surprisingly lively. We made a right and stumbled upon a big decorative window and a small door. There was some Chinese lettering written above. Although we were looking for it we weren’t as fluent in Chinese as we thought. Lol. Tiger fork has a unique ambiance with the bar front and center. There’s a long table in the middle and several other tables on the side of the room. All the way in the back of the restaurant is the kitchen fully open for everyone to see. We skipped what looked like a small wait. And were directed toward two seats at the “chef’s table” a counter right in front of the kitchen.  Our server greeted us in no time although they were super busy. We came on a recommendation for a while fish menu item. We were directed to the market fish. Just the description alone was enough to get our mouths watering. No more than 15 mins later we saw, what we hoped at the time,  were our identical dishes being plated. The dorade, a white fish, was filleted cut into tasty chunks, fried, and tucked under the remaining body of the fish which was also fried and contained more edible chunks. The jasmine rice came on the side in a small separate bowl. The presentation was eye catching to say the least. And the sauce... OMG the sauce was AMAZING. The meal is a pretty big portion (as a some for later guy I was happy to get a doggy bag) so the $32 price tag was justified. Overall an excellent menu item. I would definitely go back. As the menu item is a bit vague I’m sure they have other types of fish that come in similar preparations. So the dorade may not be there forever but it def worth the trip to see what their next market fish dish is!!  Delicious sauce Filet fish fried Presentation was amazing Served with jasmine rice $32
Amazing food, great service and atmosphere. Don't miss this place.

Everything about this restaurant was pretty great. From walking through the alley ways to come to a huge window with Chinese writing above a black door. The service and staff was incredible all the food looked great, but the dorade whole fish was good, so good that after I took a bite I stared at it trying to figure out what it was comprised of on a molecular level.

A friend and I wandered into Tiger Fork while exploring blagden alley. Their fun cocktails supposedly detox, energize, calm anxiety, heal and there's an aphrodisiac blend that could come in handy. Ours (the 8 o'clock for fatigue - it has ginseng - & the classic with gin - it has gin & chili oil ) were delicious and playful though gimmicky - all I wanted was a good Buzz and got a weee one. The eggplant dish was way too salty for my taste, the wanton was way too oily (keto?) but delicious, and the egg noodle shrimp dish was phenomenally phenomenal comfort food so stupid good we ordered two servings. Dreaming about it. The bubble waffle dessert is ok, I disliked that it was served  propped up  on  a cushion of brown  paper; a plate or shallow dish would make a much better presentation. It too is playful though. The  service staff was kind & attentive, We drank a lot of water because they just kept pouring and pouring it. My friend and I left hydrated and happy to recommend Tiger Fork. Expect a fun and playful vibe.
One of DCs better bars! Super cool space and great food . Best of all an amazing team!
Good cocktails food good not amazing

Had the BBQ plate with the chili beans. It was delicious just vastly overpriced for what it was. Maybe it's a Washington priced thing but $120 later for 2 dishes which is pretty straight forward Hong Kong food and 2 cocktails seems overpriced to me.
Love this place! Great atmosphere and location. Fantastic cocktails. And the Beef chow foon is to die for... Then again everything I've eaten there is amazing.
Is good food

Maybe I just ordered the wrong things, but I was really disappointed given how much good reviews this place got. I ordered beef chow fun and it was 50% sauce. It was so sweet and salty and I couldn't finish it. Definitely the dish to avoid ordering there.

worst service I've ever seen...  stood waiting for a greeter for 10 minutes... several bartenders and servers noticed me waiting, but no one helped me or acknowledged me... sadddd saddd place you are...

After living in Hong and China for 2+ years, I’ve been able to find some authentic Chinese food in the US. But I consistently had to choose between getting authentic tasting Chinese food while sitting on plastic stools with rushed, inattentive service OR really nice ambiance & service but over-sugared & over-breaded food (i.e. inauthentic food). I could never have both, until Tiger Fork.  They nailed the authentic Hong Kong food, trimmed down the menu to the essential dishes, and they paired great food with amazing service.  It’s pricey, but worth every penny.  Highlights: Cheung Fun (rolled up rice noodles with delicious sauce), HK Green Beans (side dish), Salted Fish & Prawn Fried Rice (the manager suggested pouring the sauce and green beans onto the rice.  I’ve never had a better fried rice), BBQ Plate Combo (bbq pork, chicken, and crispy pork belly to die for), and try some of the Chinese Medicine cocktail drinks - they are great!
Super nice food. Not a regular chinese place
Great cocktails (try the orange cinnamon one, they light it on fire!) and quality family style Chinese food

I walked in warning myself this isn't going to be authentic, is fusion food. HK Milk Tea just mediocre, not hot enough and not smooth enough and comes sweeten. You must use use both condensed milk and evaporated milk to get the right flavor. I know im being picky but Milk Tea is the Jewel of Hong Kong. Next, Dan Dan noodles, ehhhh, noodles are way too soft, flavor not bad. Cheung Fun is not bad, worth giving it a try. Egg tart, I can get it at the Great Wall grocery in Virginia and is better. The Beef Chow Fun is like they just stir together the sauce with all the ingredients...disappointed. Chow Fun is all about power/fire of the wok and this just doesn't have it. Well I may still come back to try the brunch menu, it's a completely different set of dishes so maybe that will be better.

Had the pork ribs and fried rice. The fried rice was a bit clumpy (rice was cooked with too much water) and didn't have the wok flavor that fried rice is supposed to have. The pork ribs had good flavor and nice presentation, but the meat was tough and dry. Overall food was mediocre. Atmosphere was nice and wait staff was attentive.
Entrees were good but small. The fortune cookies have the best fortunes. Their automated text reservation system has typos.

Google for the win again!  This place is outstanding.  Staff was great!! Food was AMAZING!  Pork ribs again and again and again please.  Cocktails also delicious.  Don't hesitate to check this place out.

I enjoy the food at Tiger Fork, but the house needs some improvement. During brunch, nearly half of the tables were available but apparently management will not allow their staff to seat even a two top with one person while they are waiting for their second party to arrive. I watched both myself and another table (4 top albeit) order food from the bar just as they were waiting only for the need for ALL of the food to be carried over to the space that was readily available beforehand. In addition, the staff only helped move the plates after being asked. Additionally, the wait staff were understaffed and things took a pretty long time for DC standards. Additionally, people were serving themselves from other tables and not everyone was offered place settings when arriving. I won’t be coming back for brunch again.
The food is always amazing and the drinks are too, however, I feel the drinks are overpriced for what you get - even for DC.

Since I arrived late, only the late night menu was available (4 items).  The fried chicken was pretty good.  I thought the bartender told me it came with rice but when I got the bill, I was charged $3 for the rice.  A little excessive for a small bowl of rice.

Arrived on an unplanned Saturday evening around 6:30. Wait time for a table was about two hours. Bar seating is open. We, party of two, stalked patrons at the bar and commandeered seats after about 40 minutes. Food was flavorful and served family style. Lots of hearty rice noodles options with vegetarian choices. The drinks were sumptuous. Due to open space design noise level could be quite high.
Wonderful.  Chinese/ Hong Kong food

Restaurant and decor was awesome.  The alley scene was really cool (came from Baltimore). My partner and I came for my birthday.  The service was pretty good, we waited quite some time to get out check, but we didn’t mind, it was extremely busy.  The vibe was awesome.  The homeopathic drinks were very cool.  We definitely had a lapse in service in which adequate recovery was made (we didn’t ask for it-just common industry standard.).  We ordered our main course at about 9:55 pm, it was around 10:25 pm when our BBQ platter came out and we were informed they were out of the other item we ordered, the Dan noodles.  We understand these things happen, but for 30 mins the chef never notified anyone that they only had X amount of Dan noodles left is a pretty big lapse in judgement.  And to also notify us whilst bringing out our platter saying “well I was going to bring your noodles out with this but chef said we are sold out.”  My partner doesn’t eat a lot of pork and she was very much so looking forward to Dan noodles.  Again, adequate recovery was made and we left happy, but this is certainly a teachable moment for you guys to improve your already awesome spot.  Chef has to know what’s in his kitchen and how much.  Cheers.
It's the owner

We went after dinner for a drink on a Friday night and the place was pretty lively all around the bar and at the tables. We found a spot near the wall at the bar to grab some drinks, and also ended up getting a few food menu items. The bartenders were awesome, helpful with drinks and just overall friendly and happy to be there! The drink with the burnt cinammon stick is amazing - though we can never remember what it's called! One of the food items we ordered was the bubble waffle ice cream. The first time it came out, honestly, it was inedible. The waffle could barely be cut into and the ice cream flavor was beyond weird. Our bartender not only immediately took it away upon notifying him, he also immediately went to inform the kitchen staff. He totally didn't have to do that, but wow what service. The kitchen manager came over to address the situation, and brought over a fresh dessert (waffle quality much more fresh) and a different ice cream. We did not expect such service recovery in a bar, so it was super refreshing.
Amazing dim sum! Definitely go here for an exciting and atypical brunch.
Best restaurant and atmosphere for Chinese food in the area.  To date nothing can compare.  Highly recommended if you like good quality food.
The service is really slow for food delivery

I would give the restaurant deco and mood a five star, but the food.  The food is trying too hard to be mainstream hipster, if that is a description, to be good. Innovative cocktail recipe that looks interesting on paper, but not really good tasting either. Meh, go for the mood I guess.
The fun noodles are to die for

A fork would have been lovely to devour all that the tiger was offering us!  Tiger Fork is imaginative, local, hidden and firing on all cylinders!  The scene is something out of the meatpacking district in NYC.  Great drinks followed by a simple menu that excels at letting you experience a journey into Hong Kong style cooking.  Family friendly but it is really a hot date spot.  I could start by explaining the meal (dim-sum, beef chow fun & beef and shrimp friend rice) but the experience is best explained with a question; Are you ready to drop your local chinese food provider?  Because you will!  Tiger Fork does not disappoint!

The brunch menu is quite limited, especially if you don't eat meat. We ordered the char siu bun, congee, egg tart, and green beans.  The congee was decent but don't expect the same airy, crispy dough stick you'd find in Asia. The green beans was a bit undercooked but had a decent sauce. The char siu bun is not steamed. It seemed to be baked so the filling inside was dry. My friend complained about the bun and they were generous to comp all our food ($30 value). Couldn't give 3.5 stars but since they comped us, giving 4.  On a side note, they won't seat you till your whole patty arrives, but great service when it comes to booking reservations.

Went for brunch. It’s expensive for dim sum; I think my mom would kill me if she knew I spent that much for Chow fun, but it is DC and good Chinese food is hard to come by around here. You have to go to Rockville, MD for real Chinese food. But tiger fork was good. They don’t have all the traditional dishes, they’ve added a western twist to some others. It’s interesting. The restaurant is hard to find! You can’t see it from the road/sidewalk. You have to go thru an alleyway that leads to another open area with  more businesses (and art stuff).
Really enjoyed the cocktails, food and ambiance/decor. Service was above average - fairly professional and not particularly friendly - but it was efficient.
Not Chinese dim sum. The service is horrible. We ordered the tea Which never brought over, the.congee was Really cold.
Big trouble in China feel... Epic modern fusion Chinese. Each dish delicately prepared to flourish the palate. You like garlic sesame chili? Get in here.

Yes the ambience/decor is nice for a "Chinese" restaurant, food is mediocre at best. But considering how expensive it is even for an "Asian fusion" restaurant, I gave it 2 stars. The $42 "BBQ combo plate" is a huge disappointment, both the quality and quantity of the char siu (叉燒) are subpar. Won't come again. I understand the need to have a decent, nice-looking dim sum themed restaurant that people have easy access to (don't want to drive to the suburbs of MD/VA), but with 3x-4x higher than the price you pay at an authentic dim sum spot, Tiger Fork is just bad.
Great food. Great flavors and portion sizes. Cool vibe.

This place was a giant disappointment.  From all the hype you’d expect elevated dishes but instead I got greasy, carelessly made dishes and hair in my food.  The sauce that came with the egg rolls was AWFUL. I had to spit it out, it tasted like hand sanitizer. No lie.  The sauce that came with the wontons (doused in oil) had ZERO flavor.  With that, the food was all around terrible and left me feeling sick. I’d rather get cheap Chinese delivery than ever eat here again.  If you want elevated asian food go to Chiko, same price range but a million times better.

Tiger fork, a unique find in the back alley ways... delicious Asian infusion eatery! We enjoyed the Dan Dan cold noodle lamb pasta and drank the immune system and the detox cocktail beverages 😋 awesome way to end the night
Food is okay. But dishes are small and expensive. And we waited one hour for our seats.

Definitely a great place to eat..
Was good
I thoroughly enjoyed the beef chow fun dish. Dan Dan noodles were a little bland compared to authentic versions. Drinks were on point.

Average, no chinese soup, not typical chinese but more of Asian fusion cuisine i consider. Only few dishes especially roast pork, char siew, soy chicken platter is acceptable. Nice ambience and vibe though.
Extremely nice staff and amazing, authentic food! My cousin from Hong Kong liked the food better than the food in Hong Kong. Definitely get the bubble waffle dessert (to share).
Over priced joint with just so/so food.
Delish
Great food, great service. Fried rice is yummy and filling, pork ribs are to die for. 😋
Great Asian fusion in a stylish place.

This place is amazeballs.  Came in and they were fully booked, so we started with cocktails. They are all "medicinal" - hard to explain, but go in and see for yourself. They were all good (and boozey) and they add items to their drink menu seasonally.  After a bit we were offered a seat at the chef's counter where we got to watch all the chefs cook. It was so much fun - great atmosphere, high energy yet easy going at the same time. And you could tell they pay a lot of attention to detail in their cooking and presentation.  But....THE FOOD. You will legitimately never eat fried rice anywhere else ever again after trying theirs. Also, the ribs! Order them. And, the nice thing is there are vegetarian options, too. We tried the snow peas and the beans - both great. The cucumber salad is really refreshing. I liked the beans, but, warning, they are a bit spicy. I honestly would shut my eyes and point anywhere on this menu and have confidence that whatever dish it lands on will be delicious.  Also, the staff - the manager Glenn was so lovely. He made sure we had a top notch experience and honestly, it felt like we were the only ones in the restaurant for a while. He explained and recommended dishes, gave advice on what drinks to pair, and was just a really nice guy.  To sum it up, I live in Atlanta and was in DC for a conference when I ate there. I'm here again a week later and going back tonight.
Food subpar. Duck “taco” tough and flavorless. Staff pretentious and not very hospitable
Excellent cocktails and a upbeat vibe. Perfect date spot. Every dish I tried was spot on. Service is very attentive.
Dan Dan noodles were great with the cumin lamb. Generous serving of meat and noodles (had a kick so if you can't do spicy, probably not for you). The bao was really salty.

Wow what a fun date place. If you have a reservation the host will not seat you until my whole group was there. I have friends who are always late so I knew this would an issue. I decided to sit at the bar and order food while I waited. My friend and I stayed at the bar since we got comfortable. The food was decent. I was not terribly impressed with the dumplings they were extremely greasy but overall tasty. The server was friendly and helpful. The drinks were the reason for me to come back. Great place to come for a cocktail and light bite.
Best modern Chinese restaurant in Washington
Fantastic
A little hard to find, but it disappears when you walk in. The food, decor and service were outstanding.
Great food and service.
Amazing food and service!

This was one my favorite stops I made in DC when I was visiting. The food was delicious and the cocktails were very creative. Service was excellent and ambiance was on point. When I'm in town again I'll definitely be making a stop here.
The drinks here are amazing

Love the decor and ambiance of this place, but the food is just okay. If you want really good Chinese food, make your way to MD. The BBQ platter was $42 and came with hardly any meat. Service could also be thoroughly improved, had to flag the staff for everything - ordering, getting dessert, more water, the check. Also, no one once checked to see how the meal was going.
Best Hong Kong style food around

Can I just say wow? This is coming from an Vietnamese person who grew up eating at authentic Chinese restaurants that were hot or miss.  DC is doing something no other city seems to be doing. Refining authentic chinese dishes.  Most Americans do not even realize there is menu past cashew chicken and orange chicken.  This is very much American Chinese food.  Have you ever had Chow Fun? Have you ever had crispy pork belly from Eden? Have you had Chinese barbecue? Did you even know the Chinese have their own barbecue? Most likely not.  This is one of the best places to go for the first couple waves of refined Chinese foods. The dishes I had were perfection of foods I had been enjoying since I was a young man.  I have to start with the Chow fun with brisket. To die for. If you are unsure start here. Flavors are very close to Pad See Ew if you are a thai food fan. This is wide rice noodle dish! The textures are chewy and slimy! The sauce is delicious. They used a brisket which was soft and tender.  This is the best version of this dish I have ever had.  When I typically order this dish from authentic Chinese restaurants it comes with various issues.  For example, its not hot. All the noodles are stuck together. It is under sauced. The sauce only reaches half the dish. Its missing veggies. The meat is over cooked. So for Tiger Fork to nail this dish means a lot to me. Chinese food can be amazing when cooked correctly with passion. Tiger fork does just that. I had a couple of their other dishes too but I did not want to drag out this review.  The other dishes were also perfect. I look forward to trying the rest of the menu. I have to come back!

Decent place and food was good. However, their waiting area is minuscule and we had to wait outside the establishment. If it were to rain or snow, that's not acceptable.  Location was also incredibly difficult to find. Maps kept taking us to stores on the opposite side.  Food was decent.
The five stars are for the fried rice. It sounds unappealing but their take on it makes it a real sleeper. The cocktails are packed with holistic remedies and taste like it. Stick to beer and wine.
Fun walk to the place, fab decor, unique plates and the waiter gave us free 2 cocktails due to an ordering "mistake" at another table.
Wonderful food and excellent, helpful , friendly service
Great service, amazing cocktails and the food was fantastic
Good food Ok service
Awesome vibe and food but the selection left me craving for more. Interesting fusion flavor  without making it too americanized. Love the interior. Definitely a must in DC.
My favorite DC eatery. Drinks creative. Food delicious.
Not authentic,  extremely soggynoodles..if you come here, enjoy the ambiance and just order drinks!
Staff is fantastic! Food was unique and tasty! Will definitely try again next time in town!

Definitely recommend the cuisine. I tried their fried fish, dan dan noodle and chili wonton, every single one tasted good! The price is reasonable a tiny bit pricey but worth it. The mural paintings looked great.
Excellent. Get the won tons and the chicken fried rice!
Just mediocre and expensive.
Delicious. Great service. Fascinating cocktails.
It is not an authentic Hong Kong style cuisine,  but have friendly staff.  Limited menu selection.  Highly recommend their Cheung Fun.
The cocktails we're delightful and exotic and the late night menu was delicious, well priced and super yummy.

After reading all the great reviews, we were excited to come, but were very disappointed.   All food came out within minutes of ordering- all tasted like it had been made in advance and just sitting around. We will not be back
Good food, but a little pricey. You're here more for the ambiance

We just arrived in Washington today and we were fancy to get some proper chinese food. So we found this restaurant and decided to go for it. It’s a little hard to find behind an other restaurant but inside it is very well designed and were probably a little late but that wasn’t an issue. The service was really kind and the food was outstanding! A really really big suggestion to go there from my side!

It would be a disservice to both Tiger Fork and Hong Kong cuisine as a whole to simply say "Tiger Fork is the best". This restaurant and bar reach beyond the conventions to bring diners a taste excursion of unique stature. Of special note are the medicinal cocktails, house sodas and fine sake selection. When selecting dishes, one can't really go wrong. However, you're hellbent on being right, pick the clams. Oh the clams! Also, the dan dan noodles, Chow Fun, or Market Fish will do the palate good!

This was a wonderful restaurant, I found it on Google it's a little hidden, but will worth seeking out. The ambiance inside is eclectic and fun. Great wall murals and decor. The food was delicious I had the salted fish and prawn fried rice and the Soya chicken which melted in my mouth.
Best restaurant in DC hands down
Awesome awesome awesome. Try the beef chow fun and their great cocktails.
Great Hong Kong-esque restaurant and bar with adventurous cocktails and good food.
Delicious

The Tiger Fork does a lot of interesting things with flavors; some are reminiscent of authentic or traditional cuisines while others really, really miss the mark. But at least I can guarantee your taste buds won’t be bored here. The entrance may be a little hard to find on Maps; it’s down the alley in the middle of the block behind a heavy door. The décor is a cross between a Chinese restaurant and a hip bistro, with ample brick and wooden benches accented by hanging lanterns. The herbal cocktails were creative but strange; it’s like someone looked at some themes in traditional Chinese medicine and threw it into alcohol hoping it would work. The dan dan noodles only tasted spicy, with no depth of flavor backing it. The tofu and pork skin (Chili tofu) was actually pretty good-savory, umami, and a kick. The service was great, very attentive servers.

The beef chow fun was so delicous. Make sure to ask about any secret dishes not on the menu the night you go. Although, I wasn't crazy about the secret dish, everything else was good. The menu was quite small, and not typical Chinese, it's more traditional plates.

Hands down the best stop for Chinese fare in DC right now. Leave your bland taste buds at the door and get ready to be transported to a land where flavor is king.  The seafood fried rice and Chairman’s Clams are a powerful combination, and my personal favorite. I could probably eat these dishes once (or twice) a day for the rest of my life.  For the vegetarians out there, rest easy. The Chili Tofu is as flavorful as it is sinfully delicate. Pair with the XO Asparagus for a rounded experience.  The herbal cocktails are as refreshing as they are addictive. Not to mention the pan-Asian beer selection is one of the more diverse I’ve seen in DC. I highly recommend the (dangerously) easy-drinking Tiger Beer to start.  Finally, the staff, under the management of a seasoned GM, are some of the most fun people working in the industry today. Come ready to make new friends and relax.
Crossing the threshold is like stepping  into an Asian country.
Tasty & unique.
Amazing food and service. Thank you, JC.

We sat at the chef's table which is always fun. We ordered the BBQ plate which was tasty and plentiful for 2 people to share. We also ordered the Market fish and brocolli. The fish was salty because of the Soya sauce but still edible with rice. The service was wonderful!! We got a complimentary order of wontons to start. Wontons were fresh and tasty.

One of my favorite restaurants in the area. Finding reservations for the same week may be challenging, but eating at the bar is always a great option! Love the noodles, drinks can be a bit overpriced for what they are

We had a delightful experience at Tiger Fork. The house cocktails were to die for, you absolutely can't go wrong with any choice on the list. Since this was the first time the majority of our party had visited (myself included), our waiter was a godsend in helping break down the best dishes to order. You can't go wrong at Tiger Fork!
Always great service with a lively crowd and delightful Cantonese menu!
Very good food.  Noisy, hipster atmosphere and limited beer selection.  Rapid, attentive service.
Amazing Asian bar!

I don't really want to award stars, more of a giving info to others... I've eaten here before and found it enjoyable enough. Their website says Monday-Thursday 10pm-12am late night menu....Given I live nearby and was working late, I called by on a Monday at 10.15pm to get some take-out.  But I was told then told at the bar they don't do it on Mondays... They need to update their website.

Unbelievable. Terrible, over priced, overly salty food. Very few Asians except the 3 seen at the bar. The place is loud. People were happily drinking. Examples of food: $36 for a fried, salty, greasy muddy tasting fish with a strange sauce. $15 for 4 small pieces salty pork ribs. We were starving but could not finish the muddy tasting fish. Look at the size of the chow fun dish. I think it was $18. I have to say it is the worst food I have had in years. This is not a spin on any kind of Chinese food. To add insult, my bill was handed to me in a lucky red envelope. You give people gifts in the red envelope, not bills. We got 3 fortune cookies for 4 people.  My son teased that maybe the fortune will cancel out any jinx from the red envelope curse. My cookie was empty. No fortune.
